                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.3 B 1/88</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Harding</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-08-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 2, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Just a line to acknowledge
                    yours of August 2nd, in which you write me concerning the Arms Traffic
                    Convention of September 10, 1919, which has never been submitted to the Senate
                    for approval. Inasmuch as I have already expressed to you in a personal
                    interview my belief in the utter futility of seeking a ratification at the hands
                    of the Senate I fully approve of the communication addressed to the Secretary
                    General of the League of Nations advising him of the impossibility of this
                    government approving the provisions of the convention.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren G. Harding</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
